#Text=Thomas Eden
#Text=For the obstetric physician , see Thomas Watts Eden .
#Text=For the Treasurer of Ceylon , see Thomas Eden ( civil servant ) .
#Text=For the cricketer , see Thomas Eden ( cricketer ) .
#Text=Thomas Eden ( died 18 July 1645 ) was an English jurist , academic and politician who sat in the House of Commons from 1640 to 1645 .
#Text=Background

#Text=Eden was the youngest son of Richard Eden of South Hanningfield , Essex and his wife Margaret Payton , daughter of Christopher Payton of Bury St. Edmunds , Suffolk , and was born in the south part of Sudbury within the county of Essex .
#Text=From Sudbury school , he was sent to Pembroke Hall , Cambridge . [ 1 ]
#Text=He migrated to Trinity Hall , Cambridge , where he was admitted a scholar on 31 December 1596 .
#Text=He was elected to a fellowship 10 July 1599 , and afterwards he held the office of reader of civil law in his college for many years .
#Text=On 10 November 1613 , being then LL.B. , he was chosen to succeed Clement Corbet as Professor of Law at Gresham College , London .
#Text=In March 1615 , he held a disputation for the degree of LL.D. before James I at Cambridge , which earned great applause .
#Text=He was created doctor in the following year .
#Text=On 4 November 1615 , he was admitted a member of the College of Advocates at Doctors ' Commons . [ 1 ]
#Text=Eden was elected Member of Parliament ( MP ) for Cambridge University in 1626 . [ 2 ]
#Text=On 4 September 1626 , he was chosen master of Trinity Hall on the resignation of Dr. Corbet . [ 1 ]
#Text=He was re-elected MP for Cambridge University in 1628 and sat until 1629 when King Charles decided to rule without parliament for eleven years . [ 2 ]
#Text=He was appointed chancellor of the diocese of Ely in 1630 and he was also commissary of Westminster , Bury St. Edmunds , and Sudbury , and one of the masters in chancery . [ 1 ]
#Text=In April 1640 , Eden was re-elected MP for Cambridge in the Short Parliament . [ 2 ]
#Text=He resigned his professorship at Gresham College on 27 July 1640 . [ 1 ]
#Text=In November 1640 , he was re-elected MP for Cambridge University for the Long parliament . [ 2 ]
#Text=On 3 May 1641 , he joined with those members of the House of Commons who took the Protestation .

#Text=The speaker informed the house on 7 Sept. 1642 that he had received commission from Dr. Eden and that he was also willing to lend £200 for the service of the king and parliament according to the propositions , to add to previous loans .
#Text=On 28 February 1644 , he took the Solemn League and Covenant .
#Text=In April 1645 , he was one of the committee of parliament , consisting of six peers and twelve commoners , which was appointed by the two houses to manage the affairs of the admiralty .
#Text=Eden died in London on 18 July 1645 , and was buried on 2 August in the chapel of Trinity Hall , Cambridge , where a mural monument with a Latin inscription was erected to his memory .
#Text=A Latin oration was delivered at his funeral by Thomas Exton . [ 3 ]
#Text=Eden , who was highly commended as an advocate by Thomas Fuller , was a munificent benefactor to Trinity Hall .
